Singleton ticker services are a specific architectural pattern used in AlgoChanakya for managing     WebSocket connections efficiently. Let me break this down:                                                         
                                                                                                                       What is a Singleton?                                                                                                                                                                                                                      A singleton is a design pattern where only one instance of a class exists throughout the entire application          lifecycle. Everyone shares that single instance.                                                                   

  Why Singleton for WebSocket Ticker Services?

  WebSocket connections are expensive and persistent:
  - They take time to establish
  - They maintain a continuous connection to the broker (SmartAPI/Kite)
  - Creating one per user would be wasteful and hit broker API limits

  Solution: Create one shared WebSocket connection that all users subscribe through.

  The Two Singleton Ticker Services

  From the codebase:

  1. SmartAPI Ticker Service

  # backend/app/services/legacy/smartapi_ticker.py (line 492)
  smartapi_ticker_service = SmartAPITickerService()  # Global singleton

  2. Kite Ticker Service

  # backend/app/services/legacy/kite_ticker.py (similar pattern)
  kite_ticker_service = KiteTickerService()  # Global singleton

  How It Works

  Architecture:
                  ┌─────────────────────────┐
                  │  SmartAPI/Kite Broker   │
                  │   (WebSocket Server)    │
                  └───────────┬─────────────┘
                              │
                      One WebSocket Connection
                              │
                  ┌───────────▼─────────────┐
                  │  Singleton Ticker       │
                  │  (smartapi_ticker_      │
                  │   service)              │
                  └───────────┬─────────────┘
                              │
              ┌───────────────┼───────────────┐
              │               │               │
       ┌──────▼──────┐ ┌─────▼──────┐ ┌─────▼──────┐
       │  User 1 WS  │ │  User 2 WS │ │  User 3 WS │
       │  Client     │ │  Client    │ │  Client    │
       └─────────────┘ └────────────┘ └────────────┘


before asking questions, you understand the frammework being used for this App.                                    
  Multibroker infra is being setup for two purpose
1. Any user can login to App and view live market data, OHLC from any available broker API like AngelOne SmartAPI, Zerodha Kite, Dhan API etc where logged in user won't have to provide his own broker login details. Here pp  
   App owner's API (free or paid) for these brokers will beused.                                                      
2. Any user can login to App using their own broker credentials where he will see the market data from App     
  Owner's API from any available broker but to place order, logged in User's broker API for that logged in user      
  will be used. To make this happen, you need to capture logged in user's refresh token and other needed details     
   to allow him to place orders

  My Updated Understanding
                                                                                                                     
  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  TIER 1: Market Data (APP OWNER's APIs)             │
  │                                                      │
  │  App owner has accounts with AngelOne, Zerodha, etc.│
  │  ONE shared connection per broker → serves ALL users │
  │  Users see live ticks, OHLC without their own creds │
  │  Cost: App owner pays (SmartAPI=FREE, Kite=₹500/mo) │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘

  ┌─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┐
  │  TIER 2: Order Execution (USER's OWN Broker)        │
  │                                                      │
  │  User logs in with THEIR OWN broker credentials     │
  │  App captures refresh_token for persistent access   │
  │  Orders placed via USER's broker API                │
  │  Market data still from Tier 1 (app owner's APIs)   │
  └─────────────────────────────────────────────────────┘


